sec.p:
♀♀ of Eurycanthinae often possess a beak-like ovipositor, which was erroneously stated to be formed by an elongated subgenital and supraanal plate (epiproct) by almost all former authors, e.g.
Günther, 1953 ;
Beier, 1968 ;
Bradley & Galil, 1977 ;
Zompro, 2001 . In fact, detailed examination of the female’s genitalia has shown this ovipositor to be formed by elongation of the subgenital plate and anal segment (tergite X). The supraanal plate of Eurycanthinae is small, roughly triangular and usually hidden underneath the elongation of the anal segment (
). This was only recognized by
Bradler ( 2003 )
who stated: “The dorsal part of the secondary ovipositor of the Eurycanthinae and "Neopromachini" is formed by the elongated abdominal segment 10 instead of the epiproct. This is a synapomorphic character of both taxa“. Furthermore,
Bradler ( 2003 )
proposed the term “Eurycanthomorpha” for Eurycanthinae + Neopromachini, but this appears unnecessary as Neopromachini can be regarded a tribe of Eurycanthinae . The areolate Heteropterygidae , in contrast, have the ovipositor formed by the subgenital plate and a conspicuously elongated supraanal plate (
).

Heteropterygidae (Areolatae: Bacilloidea) are the only family of Phasmatodea in which ♀♀ have the ovipositor formed by the subgenital plate and, in contrast, a conspicuously elongated supraanal plate (
). Due to the fact that two rather distinct types of ovipositor are found within Bacilloidea
Zompro, 2004 as well as two distinct types of internal micropylar plates of the eggs (open in Heteropterygidae and sections of Bacillidae but closed in Anisacanthidae ) the monophyly of this suprafamily is questionable.

